-- ── Less Annoying CRM ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Less Annoying CRM is a simple, single-price CRM built for small businesses that want contact and pipeline management without complexity.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (flat, single tier)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$15/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2009, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Around 25 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$St. Louis, Missouri, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Less Annoying CRM Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Less Annoying CRM review 2026: features, the single $15/user/month pricing plan, pros and cons, and how it compares to other small-business CRMs.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Less Annoying CRM, often abbreviated LACRM, is a customer relationship management tool built specifically for small businesses that find larger CRM platforms like Salesforce or HubSpot overwhelming, expensive or bloated with features they never use. The company was founded in 2009 by brothers Tyler King and Bracken King in St. Louis, Missouri, and has remained a private, bootstrapped and profitable business ever since, never raising outside venture funding. That independence is central to the product's philosophy: rather than chasing enterprise features and complex tiered pricing, Less Annoying CRM has stuck to a single flat price and a single feature set for every customer, explicitly rejecting the freemium and feature-gating model common across the CRM category. The company today employs roughly 25 people spread across multiple continents but has kept its headquarters and cultural center in St. Louis, and it has built a reputation, particularly among long-time users, for stability, responsive customer support, and resisting the temptation to bolt on complexity as the product has matured over more than fifteen years. Architecturally, Less Annoying CRM is a straightforward cloud-based web application hosted on Amazon Web Services, accessible from any browser or mobile device, with data encrypted in transit and backed up regularly; it does not offer a large ecosystem of native integrations or an app marketplace the way larger CRMs do, instead exposing a REST API and lightweight integrations such as Zapier connectivity, Google Calendar and Outlook syncing, and email logging via BCC or a Gmail/Outlook add-on. Core features include unified contact and company records, custom pipelines for tracking deals or projects through stages, task and calendar management with reminders, lead tracking, custom fields and custom user permissions for team-based access control, and simple reporting. Every customer gets 25GB of file storage per user, unlimited contacts, unlimited pipelines and unlimited custom fields, all as part of the base subscription rather than gated behind higher tiers. Pricing is the most distinctive part of the product: a single plan costs $15 per user per month, with no contracts, no tiered feature restrictions and no hidden add-on fees, billed monthly with the ability to cancel at any time. New users get a 30-day free trial that does not require a credit card and provides full, unrestricted access to every feature so prospective customers can evaluate the entire product rather than a limited trial version. The target audience is squarely small businesses and independent professionals, including insurance agents, real estate agents, consultants, nonprofits and small sales teams, who need to track contacts and deals but do not have a dedicated CRM administrator and do not want to pay for capabilities aimed at large enterprise sales organizations. Its main competitors in the small-business CRM space include Pipedrive, HubSpot's free and starter CRM tiers, Zoho CRM, Insightly and Nutshell, most of which use tiered pricing structures with features locked behind higher-cost plans. Less Annoying CRM differentiates itself primarily through radical simplicity and pricing transparency: because there is only one plan, customers never have to worry about being upsold, running into an unexpected paywall, or discovering that a needed feature was reserved for a higher tier. The tradeoff is that the product intentionally lacks some of the advanced automation, AI features, and deep third-party integrations found in larger competitors, which the company treats as a deliberate choice rather than an oversight, positioning itself for the segment of the market that values ease of use, predictable pricing and strong human customer support over an expansive feature set. Over its history the company has consistently emphasized customer-funded growth, profitability and long-term sustainability rather than rapid scaling, which has made it something of a reference case in the bootstrapped-SaaS community for building a durable, modestly sized software business without outside investors.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '25b50035-747c-462e-a2db-a4e3b14e8c02';

